WEBVTT

00:00.000 --> 00:03.900
20,000 leagues under the sea, by Jules

00:03.900 --> 00:08.080
Verne, retold by Fiona Bedell. Penguin readers,

00:09.020 --> 00:09.600
Level 1.

00:11.280 --> 00:14.180
Chapter 1 The Giant Whale

00:15.880 --> 00:20.060
In the year 1866, a new boat came

00:20.060 --> 00:22.520
back from sea every week with the same

00:22.520 --> 00:24.640
story. A giant

00:24.640 --> 00:27.940
whale, a hundred meters long, came near our

00:27.940 --> 00:31.300
boat, the man said. The story was in

00:31.300 --> 00:31.680
the newspapers,

00:32.720 --> 00:34.520
and a lot of people talked about it.

00:35.520 --> 00:39.400
"'It wasn't a whale,' scientists said. A big

00:39.400 --> 00:43.700
blue whale is only 27 meters long. Perhaps

00:43.700 --> 00:44.040
it

00:44.040 --> 00:45.300
was a coral reef.

00:46.200 --> 00:49.580
"'But a coral reef can't send water 50

00:49.580 --> 00:52.520
meters into the air,' the seaman answered.

00:52.520 --> 00:54.440
"'This animal can.'

00:56.020 --> 00:59.320
"'It went near one boat in Australian waters.

01:00.140 --> 01:03.680
Three days later, it was 700 leagues away

01:03.680 --> 01:04.800
in the Pacific.

01:05.980 --> 01:10.100
"'Wales can't swim 700 leagues in three days,'

01:10.100 --> 01:13.920
the scientist said. Perhaps it's a submarine.

01:15.100 --> 01:17.460
"'But only a country with a lot of

01:17.460 --> 01:20.300
money can build a submarine. And the same

01:20.300 --> 01:21.520
answer came back from

01:21.520 --> 01:25.520
every country. We haven't got a submarine.'

01:27.660 --> 01:31.960
"'One day, a British boat, the Scotia, was

01:31.960 --> 01:34.020
in the Atlantic. Suddenly,

01:34.460 --> 01:37.660
water started to come into the boat. The

01:37.660 --> 01:40.600
captain looked for the problem. There was a

01:40.600 --> 01:41.400
big hole in

01:41.400 --> 01:45.480
the boat. The Scotia is very strong,' he

01:45.480 --> 01:48.360
said. "'I don't understand this hole.'

01:49.150 --> 01:51.560
"'Is it the work of the giant whale?'

01:52.290 --> 01:55.860
"'To me, a French scientist, the stories of

01:55.860 --> 01:58.660
the whale were, of course, very interesting.

01:59.700 --> 02:04.560
"'In 1867, I visited New York, and newspapermen

02:04.560 --> 02:06.120
there asked me questions.

02:07.420 --> 02:10.280
"'You're famous for your book about sea animals,

02:10.620 --> 02:12.540
Mr. Aranax,' they said.

02:13.320 --> 02:16.480
"'What do you think about this giant whale?'

02:17.220 --> 02:20.840
"'The sea's very big,' I answered. And it's

02:20.840 --> 02:22.660
the home of many thousands of animals.

02:23.780 --> 02:27.860
Scientists don't know about all of them. But

02:27.860 --> 02:30.620
one small whale has a long spear on

02:30.620 --> 02:31.040
its head.

02:31.940 --> 02:34.300
Perhaps there's a giant whale with a spear,

02:34.500 --> 02:38.560
too. And perhaps this animal spear can make

02:38.560 --> 02:39.700
a hole in a

02:40.800 --> 02:44.140
boat.' A week later, a letter arrived at

02:44.140 --> 02:45.760
my hotel. It said,

02:46.440 --> 02:49.420
"'You know, of course, about the giant whale.

02:50.420 --> 02:52.480
One day this whale is going to kill

02:52.480 --> 02:52.760
people.

02:53.700 --> 02:55.860
But we are going to kill it first.

02:56.840 --> 02:58.820
Please calm and look for it with us.

02:59.340 --> 02:59.840
Our boat,

03:00.420 --> 03:03.380
the Abraham Lincoln, is waiting for you.'

03:04.180 --> 03:07.780
I wanted to see this interesting animal. I

03:07.780 --> 03:10.340
went quickly to the Abraham Lincoln with my

03:10.340 --> 03:12.020
Belgian servant, Consé.

03:13.240 --> 03:15.840
From New York, we went down the Atlantic

03:15.840 --> 03:18.840
coast of North and South America and into

03:18.840 --> 03:19.380
the Pacific.

03:20.780 --> 03:24.500
Week after week, all day and all night,

03:25.300 --> 03:26.520
the seamen watched the water.

03:27.760 --> 03:30.760
Consé and I watched with them. But we

03:30.760 --> 03:32.160
didn't see the giant whale.

03:33.500 --> 03:35.860
Only one man on the boat didn't watch

03:35.860 --> 03:40.580
the water. His name was Ned Land. Ned

03:40.580 --> 03:42.300
was a big, strong

03:42.300 --> 03:45.980
Canadian, about 40 years old. And he was

03:45.980 --> 03:47.100
a very good whaler.

03:48.080 --> 03:51.280
"'You're never going to find this whale,' he

03:51.280 --> 03:55.160
said. It was near Japan in May. But

03:55.160 --> 03:55.820
it's now July.

03:56.700 --> 04:01.180
Where is it today? The Mediterranean? The Arctic?

04:02.080 --> 04:02.780
Who knows?'

04:04.040 --> 04:07.200
For five long months, we looked for the

04:07.200 --> 04:10.220
whale. Then the men started to say,

04:10.900 --> 04:14.320
"'Perhaps Ned is right. When can we go

04:14.320 --> 04:16.580
home?' They asked their captain.

04:17.540 --> 04:21.180
But suddenly, one day, Ned said,

04:21.920 --> 04:24.840
"'There it is. I can see the giant

04:24.840 --> 04:25.760
whale.'"

04:26.380 --> 04:29.200
The animal moved very quickly in the water.

04:30.060 --> 04:31.520
It came near our boat.

04:32.680 --> 04:35.020
"'We don't want a hole in the Abraham

04:35.020 --> 04:37.020
Lincoln,' the captain said.

04:37.820 --> 04:38.700
"'Let's move away.'"

04:39.640 --> 04:43.020
"'But our boat was slow. We watched the

04:43.020 --> 04:46.340
whale. It's going to hit us,' we said.

04:47.320 --> 04:50.900
But it didn't. It went under the boat,

04:51.420 --> 04:52.500
not into it.

04:53.740 --> 04:57.120
All day, we went after the whale, but

04:57.120 --> 04:58.440
it stayed in front of us.

04:59.540 --> 05:02.760
"'We're never going to kill this animal,' the

05:02.760 --> 05:05.480
men said. It's playing games with us.

05:07.020 --> 05:09.420
But at night, the whale didn't move."

05:10.440 --> 05:14.980
"'Perhaps it's sleeping,' Ned land said. Let's get

05:14.980 --> 05:17.340
near. Be very quiet.'"

05:18.400 --> 05:21.700
Suddenly, water from the whale's back went up

05:21.700 --> 05:24.520
into the air and rained down on our

05:24.520 --> 05:24.740
boat.

05:25.680 --> 05:27.800
Then I was in the sea.

05:32.200 --> 05:34.920
Chapter 2 The Nautilus

05:36.360 --> 05:39.380
I'm not a young man, and I can't

05:39.380 --> 05:42.340
swim well. I started to go underwater.

05:43.900 --> 05:46.620
But then there was a strong hand on

05:46.620 --> 05:50.820
my back. I looked behind me. My servant

05:50.820 --> 05:51.500
was there.

05:53.160 --> 05:56.620
"'Conce, why are you in the water?' I

05:56.620 --> 05:56.920
asked.

05:57.780 --> 06:00.700
"'You were in the sea, and I wanted

06:00.700 --> 06:04.160
to stay with you. That's my job,' Mr.

06:04.320 --> 06:04.780
Aaron X.'

06:05.520 --> 06:06.540
"'Conce said.

06:07.280 --> 06:11.080
"'There's a problem with the Abraham Lincoln. It

06:11.080 --> 06:12.420
can't come back for us.

06:13.040 --> 06:15.420
Let's swim and wait for morning.'"

06:16.720 --> 06:19.980
Before morning, my legs stopped working.

06:21.380 --> 06:25.560
"'Go,' Conce, I said. I'm a dead man.

06:26.540 --> 06:29.840
But you're young and strong. You can find

06:29.840 --> 06:30.310
a boat."

06:31.320 --> 06:34.880
Then water came into my mouth, and my

06:34.880 --> 06:35.680
eyes closed.

06:38.360 --> 06:42.240
They opened a short time later. I was

06:42.240 --> 06:45.360
with Conce, a Ned land, too.

06:46.400 --> 06:52.620
"'I don't understand. We're not swimming. Where are

06:52.620 --> 06:54.100
we?' I asked.

06:54.960 --> 06:58.680
"'On the back of the giant whale,' Ned

06:58.680 --> 07:02.860
said. Then he smiled. But it's not a

07:02.860 --> 07:03.260
whale.'

07:04.560 --> 07:09.260
I looked, and he was right. We were

07:09.260 --> 07:10.480
on a submarine.

07:12.260 --> 07:14.340
"'You and I went into the sea at

07:14.340 --> 07:17.340
the same time,' Mr. Aaron X,' Ned said.

07:18.120 --> 07:22.380
"'After that, I waited here. We're okay now,

07:22.880 --> 07:26.060
but this boat can go underwater. What are

07:26.060 --> 07:26.900
we going to do then?'"

07:28.100 --> 07:31.120
Suddenly, the submarine started to move.

07:31.800 --> 07:35.380
"'Quickly,' I said. Make some noise. Hit the

07:35.380 --> 07:36.320
boat with your hands.'"

07:36.960 --> 07:41.620
A door opened, and eight men came out.

07:42.420 --> 07:44.240
We went with them into the submarine.

07:45.480 --> 07:48.320
"'Where are you taking us?' We asked the

07:48.320 --> 07:52.700
men. But they didn't answer. We arrived in

07:52.700 --> 07:53.380
a dark room.

07:54.580 --> 07:57.040
The men went away and closed the door

07:57.040 --> 07:57.760
behind them.

07:58.820 --> 08:02.060
"'Ned tried the door, but it didn't open.

08:03.080 --> 08:05.580
We're never going to escape,' he said.

08:06.240 --> 08:08.180
"'Those men are going to kill us.'"

08:10.160 --> 08:12.480
We waited for a long time in the

08:12.480 --> 08:16.740
dark room. Then the lights came on, and

08:16.740 --> 08:18.080
a man walked into the room.

08:18.900 --> 08:22.640
Perhaps he was thirty-five, or perhaps fifty.

08:23.820 --> 08:26.700
He was tall with black eyes and an

08:26.700 --> 08:28.160
interesting open face.

08:30.740 --> 08:34.240
"'In French,' I said our names, and asked

08:34.240 --> 08:39.040
for food and drink. He listened quietly. But

08:39.040 --> 08:39.860
he didn't answer.

08:41.120 --> 08:45.300
"'He doesn't understand French,' I said. "'You try,

08:45.500 --> 08:47.800
Ned. Perhaps he understands English.

08:48.900 --> 08:52.420
"'Ned talked in English. Then Consé tried in

08:52.420 --> 08:55.280
German. But they had the same problem.

08:56.940 --> 08:59.560
"'What can we do now?' I asked my

08:59.560 --> 09:02.860
friends. But the man walked away and closed

09:02.860 --> 09:03.400
the door.

09:05.180 --> 09:10.080
"'Again we waited. Ned was very angry. He

09:10.080 --> 09:11.680
didn't like the men on the submarine.

09:12.320 --> 09:15.660
"'He didn't like our room. And he didn't

09:15.660 --> 09:16.240
like waiting.

09:17.860 --> 09:21.200
"'I'm going to escape from this submarine,' he

09:21.200 --> 09:21.480
said.

09:23.140 --> 09:26.400
"'A man came into the room, and Ned

09:26.400 --> 09:28.020
started to hit him in the face.

09:29.000 --> 09:31.960
"'Consé and I wanted to stop Ned, but

09:31.960 --> 09:36.140
he was very strong. Suddenly our first visitor

09:36.140 --> 09:37.060
was with us again.

09:38.580 --> 09:42.880
"'Stop, Mr. Land,' he said, in very good

09:42.880 --> 09:43.220
French.

09:43.980 --> 09:46.780
"'And please listen to me, all of you.

09:47.740 --> 09:51.400
My name is Captain Nemo, and this is

09:51.400 --> 09:53.200
my boat, the Nautilus.

09:54.480 --> 09:56.480
"'I didn't talk to you on my first

09:56.480 --> 10:00.580
visit. I'm sorry about that. But you're a

10:00.580 --> 10:01.320
problem for me.

10:02.460 --> 10:06.160
"'What can I do with you? My men

10:06.160 --> 10:08.120
and I are never going back to our

10:08.120 --> 10:08.460
countries.

10:09.480 --> 10:11.620
"'We're always going to live on the Nautilus.

10:12.920 --> 10:15.940
You can live with us too. But you

10:15.940 --> 10:16.760
can't go back

10:16.760 --> 10:20.020
"'to your countries after that. We don't want

10:20.020 --> 10:22.020
stories in the newspapers about us.

10:23.120 --> 10:26.720
"'What are you saying?' I asked. We want

10:26.720 --> 10:27.400
to go home.

10:28.700 --> 10:32.480
"'You can go now,' he answered. But it's

10:32.480 --> 10:34.920
going to be difficult for you, because you

10:34.920 --> 10:35.620
haven't got a boat.

10:36.580 --> 10:39.540
"'You're underwater, and you aren't near the coast.

10:40.600 --> 10:43.260
Stay with us now, and you can see

10:43.260 --> 10:44.740
a lot of interesting things.

10:45.780 --> 10:47.580
"'But you can never go home.'"

10:52.320 --> 10:57.620
Chapter 3. Our first weeks underwater. We stayed,

10:58.100 --> 10:58.520
of course.

11:00.000 --> 11:02.240
We walked with Nemo's men to our new

11:02.240 --> 11:05.340
bedrooms. Then I had some food with the

11:05.340 --> 11:05.520
captain.

11:06.560 --> 11:09.940
"'Our food comes from the sea,' he said.

11:10.600 --> 11:12.080
And we eat very well.'

11:12.900 --> 11:18.000
"'Our shirts, our shoes, our beds, our pens.

11:18.840 --> 11:21.100
We make all of them from sea animals

11:21.100 --> 11:21.520
too.'

11:22.600 --> 11:26.040
"'I love the sea. It's our only friend.

11:27.200 --> 11:30.000
People can't make problems for us here.'

11:31.640 --> 11:33.480
"'But you don't want to listen to me

11:33.480 --> 11:37.040
all day. Come and see my submarine.'"

11:38.660 --> 11:41.380
We went into a room with thousands of

11:41.380 --> 11:41.600
books.

11:42.600 --> 11:45.440
"'I often read your book about sea animals,

11:45.700 --> 11:47.860
Mr. Aranax,' the captain said.

11:48.500 --> 11:51.840
"'You write very well. But your time on

11:51.840 --> 11:53.760
the nautilus is going to teach you a

11:53.760 --> 11:54.900
lot of new things.

11:55.700 --> 11:58.920
"'A submarine is a good home for a

11:58.920 --> 11:59.620
scientist.'"

12:01.180 --> 12:04.640
I visited every room on the nautilus, the

12:04.640 --> 12:08.680
first and only submarine in the seas. Captain

12:08.680 --> 12:09.140
Nemo

12:09.140 --> 12:11.640
was its builder, and he talked about his

12:11.640 --> 12:14.320
answers to the problems of an underwater boat.

12:15.360 --> 12:16.300
He was a clever

12:16.300 --> 12:22.780
scientist and a very interesting man. Later, Nared

12:22.780 --> 12:25.360
and Consé asked me about Captain Nemo.

12:26.220 --> 12:28.940
Who was he? Where did he come from?

12:29.600 --> 12:31.800
Why did he stay away from people and

12:31.800 --> 12:32.620
live underwater?

12:34.060 --> 12:36.300
But I didn't know the answers to their

12:36.300 --> 12:36.740
questions.

12:38.440 --> 12:42.980
Then, suddenly, the nautilus's sea lights came on

12:42.980 --> 12:45.200
and we stopped thinking about the captain.

12:46.780 --> 12:51.100
The sea looked very beautiful, with fish of

12:51.100 --> 12:53.660
every color big and small.

12:54.940 --> 12:57.280
We didn't take our eyes from the sea

12:57.280 --> 13:00.740
all night. Captain Nemo was right.

13:02.080 --> 13:04.960
A submarine was a good home for a

13:04.960 --> 13:05.400
scientist.

13:08.300 --> 13:11.100
The weeks after that were quiet, but interesting.

13:11.940 --> 13:15.180
The submarine usually stayed about a hundred meters

13:15.180 --> 13:15.660
underwater.

13:17.260 --> 13:19.160
But every morning we went up for air,

13:19.820 --> 13:21.620
and my friends and I looked across the

13:21.620 --> 13:23.160
blue waters of the Pacific.

13:25.260 --> 13:29.060
We didn't often see Captain Nemo, but Consé

13:29.060 --> 13:31.480
and I looked at his books and at

13:31.480 --> 13:32.360
the fish in the sea.

13:33.860 --> 13:37.140
Only Nared was unhappy. He wasn't a scientist

13:37.140 --> 13:39.220
and he didn't like reading.

13:39.960 --> 13:42.640
And he didn't like eating fish every day.

13:44.040 --> 13:46.020
One day, Captain Nemo said,

13:46.640 --> 13:48.560
there are a lot of animals in the

13:48.560 --> 13:51.680
trees of Crespo. They make good food.

13:52.560 --> 13:54.320
Do you want to look for some with

13:54.320 --> 13:54.520
me?

13:55.460 --> 13:57.540
Trees, I asked.

13:58.380 --> 13:59.600
Are we near the coast?

14:00.480 --> 14:04.100
There are underwater trees, he answered.

14:06.080 --> 14:09.420
Ned didn't want to come, but Consé and

14:09.420 --> 14:12.560
I dressed in diving suits and walked on

14:12.560 --> 14:14.460
the sea floor with the captain and his

14:14.460 --> 14:14.700
men.

14:15.540 --> 14:19.880
It wasn't difficult. On a boat, diving suits

14:19.880 --> 14:22.400
are heavy, but they are light in the

14:22.400 --> 14:22.680
water.

14:23.760 --> 14:26.980
There was only one problem. I wanted to

14:26.980 --> 14:29.560
talk about the tall trees and beautiful fish

14:29.560 --> 14:30.360
with Consé.

14:31.200 --> 14:33.460
But you can't hear people in a diving

14:33.460 --> 14:33.900
suit.

14:35.200 --> 14:37.720
Captain Nemo and his men killed some big

14:37.720 --> 14:40.400
animals, and we went back to the Nautilus

14:40.400 --> 14:42.580
with a lot of good food.

14:47.680 --> 14:50.080
Chapter 4, Papuan Spears

14:51.820 --> 14:54.940
After two months on the Nautilus, we were

14:54.940 --> 14:56.160
near the coast of Australia.

14:57.360 --> 14:59.580
Captain Nemo wanted to take us to Asia,

15:00.300 --> 15:01.760
but the seas in front of us were

15:01.760 --> 15:02.600
very difficult.

15:03.660 --> 15:05.980
The coral reefs are famous because they are

15:05.980 --> 15:09.860
beautiful, but they are famous too because boats

15:09.860 --> 15:11.100
often hit them.

15:12.000 --> 15:14.340
There are a lot of dead seamen in

15:14.340 --> 15:14.880
those waters.

15:17.440 --> 15:20.120
We went slowly and looked for coral reefs

15:20.120 --> 15:21.800
under the water in front of us.

15:22.700 --> 15:25.080
For a long time, we didn't have any

15:25.080 --> 15:25.480
problems.

15:26.380 --> 15:31.020
Then, suddenly, there was a big noise. The

15:31.020 --> 15:31.840
Nautilus stopped.

15:33.320 --> 15:37.540
What's wrong? I asked the captain. The Nautilus

15:37.540 --> 15:39.460
is sitting on a coral reef.

15:40.560 --> 15:45.480
It can't move. He answered quietly. But it's

15:45.480 --> 15:46.060
not a problem.

15:47.060 --> 15:49.620
After five days, the sea is going to

15:49.620 --> 15:50.880
take us away from here.

15:51.940 --> 15:54.700
The sea goes up and down every day,

15:54.700 --> 15:57.080
of course, and it goes up and down

15:57.080 --> 15:58.220
every month, too.

15:59.340 --> 16:00.780
Was Captain Nemo right?

16:02.720 --> 16:04.980
Ned didn't want to wait and see.

16:05.680 --> 16:09.000
We can escape from the Nautilus today, he

16:09.000 --> 16:09.220
said.

16:10.020 --> 16:11.920
The coast is near. Let's go!

16:12.580 --> 16:14.780
No, Ned, I answered.

16:15.400 --> 16:19.040
The Papuans live on that coast. Papuans often

16:19.040 --> 16:20.640
kill and eat their visitors.

16:22.140 --> 16:25.280
Every day, Ned looked across the water at

16:25.280 --> 16:26.260
the beautiful coast.

16:27.380 --> 16:30.080
Perhaps we can go there and look for

16:30.080 --> 16:31.640
food, he said.

16:32.560 --> 16:33.940
We asked the captain.

16:34.900 --> 16:38.260
Of course you can go, he said, with

16:38.260 --> 16:38.640
a smile.

16:39.780 --> 16:42.420
Take the little boat, but be back here

16:42.420 --> 16:43.240
before nighttime.

16:45.040 --> 16:47.800
Ned, Conse and I arrived on the coast,

16:48.620 --> 16:50.640
and for a long time we didn't stop

16:50.640 --> 16:51.180
eating.

16:52.540 --> 16:54.220
There was a lot of fruit on the

16:54.220 --> 16:56.920
trees, and it was very good.

16:58.460 --> 17:00.560
Conse and I looked at the beautiful animals.

17:01.680 --> 17:04.720
Ned looked at the animals, too. But he

17:04.720 --> 17:05.900
wanted them for food.

17:06.980 --> 17:09.920
He worked quickly, and that evening we had

17:09.920 --> 17:12.380
a lot of dead animals and fruit for

17:12.380 --> 17:13.420
the Nautilus' kitchen.

17:14.780 --> 17:16.900
We started to put things in the little

17:16.900 --> 17:19.820
boat. But suddenly, Conse said,

17:20.200 --> 17:23.020
Oh! What was that on my hand?

17:23.820 --> 17:27.200
Look, Ned said. There are men in the

17:27.200 --> 17:31.080
trees. They've got spears. They're going to kill

17:31.080 --> 17:31.360
us.

17:32.280 --> 17:34.380
Conse and I were quickly in the boat,

17:34.900 --> 17:36.760
but Ned wanted to get the food first.

17:37.660 --> 17:40.460
A rain of small spears came from the

17:40.460 --> 17:40.700
trees.

17:41.450 --> 17:44.360
Then 100 men started to run to our

17:44.360 --> 17:44.580
boat.

17:45.740 --> 17:48.360
We went quickly across the water to the

17:48.360 --> 17:48.740
Nautilus.

17:49.680 --> 17:52.480
The papuins stayed on the coast because they

17:52.480 --> 17:53.320
didn't have boats.

17:54.640 --> 17:58.060
In the morning, there were 600 papuins on

17:58.060 --> 18:00.880
the coast, and some of them had boats.

18:01.760 --> 18:04.040
They came across the sea to the Nautilus.

18:04.780 --> 18:07.820
We've got a big problem now, I said,

18:07.920 --> 18:08.700
to Captain Nemo.

18:09.340 --> 18:11.820
The papuins can't get into the Nautilus today

18:11.820 --> 18:13.940
because the doors are closed.

18:14.840 --> 18:16.580
But tomorrow there isn't going to be any

18:16.580 --> 18:19.360
air in here because we can't open the

18:19.360 --> 18:19.600
doors.

18:20.340 --> 18:23.060
What are we going to do then? Captain

18:23.060 --> 18:24.820
Nemo didn't look unhappy.

18:25.620 --> 18:29.240
We're going to wait and see, he said.

18:29.240 --> 18:32.560
I didn't sleep well that night.

18:33.400 --> 18:35.120
In the morning there were a lot of

18:35.120 --> 18:36.400
papuins on the Nautilus.

18:36.960 --> 18:40.520
There wasn't much air for us now, but

18:40.520 --> 18:41.920
the doors stayed closed.

18:43.480 --> 18:46.940
We're going this afternoon, the captain said.

18:47.880 --> 18:51.380
That afternoon, after five days on the coral

18:51.380 --> 18:54.780
reef, the Nautilus suddenly started to move.

18:55.840 --> 18:57.380
Captain Nemo was right.

18:58.400 --> 19:01.100
The sea was up, and the submarine was

19:01.100 --> 19:02.060
in water again.

19:03.100 --> 19:04.920
We moved quickly away from the coast.

19:05.660 --> 19:08.400
We looked back, and the papuins were in

19:08.400 --> 19:08.720
the sea.

19:09.880 --> 19:14.040
Then we opened the doors, and air came

19:14.040 --> 19:14.680
into the boat.

19:19.040 --> 19:22.000
Chapter 5 Nemo's Gold

19:23.540 --> 19:27.460
We went across Indian and Arabian waters and

19:27.460 --> 19:28.480
into the Red Sea.

19:29.400 --> 19:32.660
Ned didn't stop thinking about escape from the

19:32.660 --> 19:33.040
Nautilus.

19:34.380 --> 19:37.220
Where are we going after this? He asked.

19:38.160 --> 19:41.060
Back to the Arabian Sea first, I answered.

19:41.840 --> 19:44.240
Then perhaps down the African coast.

19:45.220 --> 19:47.220
But we didn't go back to the Arabian

19:47.220 --> 19:47.660
Sea.

19:48.780 --> 19:50.840
One day, Captain Nemo said,

19:51.500 --> 19:54.460
Tomorrow, we're going to be in the Mediterranean.

19:55.680 --> 19:56.960
I didn't understand.

19:57.940 --> 20:00.500
We can't go from the Red Sea to

20:00.500 --> 20:02.900
the Mediterranean in a boat, I said.

20:03.820 --> 20:05.860
How are we going to take the Nautilus

20:05.860 --> 20:06.760
across Egypt?

20:07.660 --> 20:12.060
We aren't going to go across Egypt, we're

20:12.060 --> 20:15.000
going to go under it, the captain answered.

20:16.060 --> 20:17.940
I know an underwater tunnel.

20:19.360 --> 20:22.160
That evening, we went into the tunnel.

20:23.060 --> 20:25.380
It was very dark and very small.

20:26.620 --> 20:29.320
But Nemo was a good seaman, and the

20:29.320 --> 20:31.040
Nautilus didn't have any problems.

20:32.040 --> 20:34.780
In a very short time, we were in

20:34.780 --> 20:35.280
the Mediterranean.

20:37.380 --> 20:39.900
We then moved quickly away from Egypt.

20:40.900 --> 20:44.060
Near Crete, I remembered stories in the newspapers.

20:45.100 --> 20:46.520
Crete was in Turkey.

20:47.940 --> 20:49.660
But the Cretans wanted to be Greek.

20:50.900 --> 20:53.360
A lot of Cretans were now dead because

20:53.360 --> 20:56.120
the Turkish people were very angry with them.

20:57.460 --> 20:58.720
I looked at the sea.

20:59.920 --> 21:02.940
There was a swimmer underwater, and he didn't

21:02.940 --> 21:03.960
have a diving suit.

21:04.880 --> 21:08.120
Quickly, I said to Captain Nemo, let's go

21:08.120 --> 21:10.140
to him now, or the sea's going to

21:10.140 --> 21:10.600
kill him.

21:11.340 --> 21:12.240
He's okay.

21:13.160 --> 21:13.920
The captain answered.

21:14.800 --> 21:18.040
His name's Nicholas, and he's a very good

21:18.040 --> 21:18.620
swimmer.

21:19.960 --> 21:21.960
Was this man a friend of the captain?

21:22.940 --> 21:26.120
I wanted to ask, but then I stopped

21:26.120 --> 21:27.500
thinking about the swimmer.

21:28.420 --> 21:31.720
Captain Nemo had gold in his hands.

21:31.720 --> 21:36.120
I looked behind him, and there was gold

21:36.120 --> 21:37.460
on the table, too.

21:38.660 --> 21:40.020
A lot of gold.

21:42.340 --> 21:44.800
Later, I listened to the noises of the

21:44.800 --> 21:44.980
night.

21:45.840 --> 21:47.840
Men went away from the Nautilus in a

21:47.840 --> 21:50.500
little boat, and came back a short time

21:50.500 --> 21:50.860
later.

21:52.300 --> 21:54.320
Did they take gold with them?

21:55.100 --> 21:56.620
Where did they take it?

21:57.940 --> 21:59.460
Was it for the Cretans?

22:01.720 --> 22:04.640
We didn't go near any coasts after this,

22:05.020 --> 22:07.100
and three days later we were in the

22:07.100 --> 22:07.460
Atlantic.

22:08.360 --> 22:09.520
Ned was angry.

22:10.160 --> 22:12.700
He wanted to escape to a European country,

22:13.240 --> 22:15.640
and Europe was behind us now.

22:16.840 --> 22:19.280
But first, we went up the coast of

22:19.280 --> 22:20.500
Portugal and Spain.

22:21.360 --> 22:24.820
We're going to escape this evening, Ned said.

22:25.520 --> 22:28.020
Meet Consé and me at the little boat

22:28.020 --> 22:29.340
at nine o'clock.

22:29.340 --> 22:33.680
I wanted to stay on the Nautilus, because

22:33.680 --> 22:35.640
it was a good home for a scientist.

22:36.720 --> 22:39.240
But I wanted to see Paris again one

22:39.240 --> 22:42.900
day, and this was perhaps the only time

22:42.900 --> 22:43.640
for an escape.

22:45.040 --> 22:47.440
Okay, I said to Ned.

22:48.900 --> 22:52.060
At nine o'clock, I opened my door

22:52.060 --> 22:54.760
and started to walk to the little boat.

22:55.560 --> 22:59.460
But suddenly, the Nautilus stopped on the sea

22:59.460 --> 23:02.220
floor, then Captain Nemo arrived.

23:03.260 --> 23:06.600
He wanted the answer to a question, I

23:06.600 --> 23:09.540
think, Mr. Aronax, he said.

23:10.480 --> 23:11.480
Come with me.

23:13.080 --> 23:14.800
I went with him to the window.

23:15.700 --> 23:17.980
There were some old boats on the sea

23:17.980 --> 23:21.220
floor, and Nemo's men were there in their

23:21.220 --> 23:21.920
diving suits.

23:22.800 --> 23:25.980
They walked to the old boats, and came

23:25.980 --> 23:27.680
back with gold in their hands.

23:29.840 --> 23:32.420
These boats went down to the sea floor

23:32.420 --> 23:36.760
in 1702, heavy with South American gold.

23:37.960 --> 23:40.500
My men and I sometimes come here and

23:40.500 --> 23:43.680
take a little gold, but it isn't for

23:43.680 --> 23:43.940
us.

23:44.840 --> 23:48.520
There are unhappy people in many countries.

23:49.920 --> 23:51.200
The gold is for them.

23:52.440 --> 23:56.480
I remembered the problems in Crete, and started

23:56.480 --> 23:58.660
to understand Captain Nemo.

24:01.020 --> 24:02.800
But Ned was not a happy man.

24:03.460 --> 24:04.800
Where were you?

24:05.460 --> 24:06.300
He asked me later.

24:07.200 --> 24:09.800
We waited for you, but you didn't come.

24:14.280 --> 24:17.220
Chapter 6 to the South Pole

24:17.220 --> 24:22.040
A day later, we were many leagues from

24:22.040 --> 24:22.500
the coast.

24:24.180 --> 24:27.000
The roads here are very bad, Mr. Aronax,

24:27.720 --> 24:28.760
Captain Nemo said.

24:29.740 --> 24:31.240
But do you want to walk on them

24:31.240 --> 24:31.660
with me?

24:33.120 --> 24:35.200
Roads under the sea.

24:36.360 --> 24:40.020
I didn't understand, but I put on my

24:40.020 --> 24:41.660
diving suit and went with the captain.

24:42.940 --> 24:44.700
Nemo walked quickly underwater.

24:44.700 --> 24:48.700
I wanted to stay with him, but it

24:48.700 --> 24:49.800
was very difficult.

24:50.800 --> 24:53.100
My feet came down on the sea floor,

24:53.700 --> 24:55.920
but the sea floor moved with me.

24:56.900 --> 24:58.540
What was under my feet?

25:00.020 --> 25:02.660
For a long time, we didn't stop walking.

25:04.260 --> 25:07.240
And then, I had the answer to my

25:07.240 --> 25:07.680
question.

25:09.200 --> 25:12.700
There were old houses on the sea floor.

25:13.560 --> 25:16.720
But why were there buildings here in the

25:16.720 --> 25:20.180
Atlantic under 300 meters of water?

25:22.020 --> 25:23.260
The sea floor went up.

25:24.160 --> 25:27.820
Captain Nemo stopped walking and started to write

25:27.820 --> 25:29.280
with his hand in the water.

25:31.360 --> 25:32.020
Atlantis!

25:33.940 --> 25:34.660
Atlantis!

25:36.640 --> 25:40.240
There were many stories about this underwater country,

25:40.980 --> 25:44.160
but for many people they were only stories.

25:45.440 --> 25:46.140
I looked down.

25:47.140 --> 25:49.940
There was a big town on the sea

25:49.940 --> 25:50.360
floor.

25:51.760 --> 25:53.420
For a long time, I didn't move.

25:54.540 --> 25:56.680
I was one of the first people in

25:56.680 --> 25:59.420
Atlantis for hundreds of years.

26:00.820 --> 26:02.700
I wanted to remember it.

26:05.960 --> 26:09.340
After our visit to Atlantis, the Nautilus didn't

26:09.340 --> 26:09.800
stop.

26:10.240 --> 26:13.140
For many weeks the sun was very strong.

26:13.940 --> 26:16.720
Then the air started to get cold, and

26:16.720 --> 26:17.980
there was ice in the sea.

26:18.900 --> 26:20.940
We were in the seas of the Antarctic.

26:22.000 --> 26:25.620
Four days after the first ice, the Nautilus

26:25.620 --> 26:26.060
stopped.

26:26.940 --> 26:30.040
There was ice in front of us, and

26:30.040 --> 26:32.040
ice behind us.

26:33.180 --> 26:36.740
We can't move, Ned said, to concise in

26:36.740 --> 26:36.940
me.

26:37.500 --> 26:39.540
How are we going to escape from the

26:39.540 --> 26:39.840
ice?

26:41.200 --> 26:43.460
But Captain Nemo came to us and said,

26:44.360 --> 26:46.700
We're going to be the first people at

26:46.700 --> 26:47.420
the South Pole.

26:48.360 --> 26:51.460
We can get there in a submarine, because

26:51.460 --> 26:52.940
there's water under this ice.

26:54.080 --> 26:55.140
There's only one problem.

26:56.080 --> 26:57.980
We can't come up for air.

26:59.200 --> 27:03.620
The Nautilus went down, and down.

27:05.020 --> 27:08.760
At 300 metres, we were under the ice,

27:09.560 --> 27:11.700
and there was water in front of us

27:11.700 --> 27:11.920
again.

27:13.160 --> 27:15.900
We started to move quickly to the South

27:15.900 --> 27:16.260
Pole.

27:17.360 --> 27:20.180
After a day, we were under a thousand

27:20.180 --> 27:21.280
metres of ice.

27:22.340 --> 27:25.380
But the morning after that, there were only

27:25.380 --> 27:26.600
50 metres of ice.

27:27.510 --> 27:33.060
Then 20, 10, 5.

27:34.720 --> 27:37.340
And then the Nautilus came up into the

27:37.340 --> 27:39.460
air, and the open sea.

27:40.980 --> 27:43.360
We were at the South Pole.

27:44.720 --> 27:49.900
It wasn't very cold, perhaps three degrees centigrade.

27:50.600 --> 27:52.960
We stayed there for three happy days,

27:53.600 --> 27:55.800
and looked at a lot of interesting animals

27:55.800 --> 27:56.560
and fish.

27:57.640 --> 27:59.440
Then we went under the ice again.

28:00.720 --> 28:03.460
That night, there was a big noise.

28:04.560 --> 28:08.260
Captain Nemo said, The ice moved at the

28:08.260 --> 28:08.940
wrong time,

28:09.840 --> 28:11.180
and now we've got a problem.

28:12.240 --> 28:16.440
We're under 300 metres of ice, but there's

28:16.440 --> 28:17.800
ice under us too.

28:19.000 --> 28:21.660
And on our left, and right.

28:23.020 --> 28:25.840
We're in a tunnel, but in front of

28:25.840 --> 28:26.500
us there's water,

28:27.420 --> 28:29.160
and it's going to take us up to

28:29.160 --> 28:29.580
the air.

28:31.260 --> 28:34.400
The Nautilus moved quickly in the tunnel, but

28:34.400 --> 28:35.700
then there was a noise again.

28:36.480 --> 28:38.560
There was now ice in front of us

28:38.560 --> 28:38.760
too.

28:39.840 --> 28:41.600
The Nautilus started to go back.

28:42.760 --> 28:43.600
The same noise.

28:44.760 --> 28:46.100
Ice behind us.

28:47.340 --> 28:50.680
We're all dead, Ned Land said.

28:51.540 --> 28:55.380
We've got air for two days, Captain Nemo

28:55.380 --> 28:55.640
answered.

28:56.420 --> 28:58.380
After that, who knows?

28:59.440 --> 29:01.460
But there are only ten metres of ice

29:01.460 --> 29:02.400
under the Nautilus.

29:03.000 --> 29:05.380
Under that, there's water again.

29:06.180 --> 29:08.020
We can make a hole in the ice

29:08.020 --> 29:09.900
with knives and spears,

29:10.740 --> 29:13.240
and the Nautilus can escape from the tunnel

29:13.240 --> 29:14.560
into open water.

29:16.040 --> 29:19.580
We dressed in diving suits and started to

29:19.580 --> 29:21.240
work with the knives and spears,

29:22.400 --> 29:23.620
but it was a big job.

29:24.480 --> 29:27.900
Perhaps four or five days work, and we

29:27.900 --> 29:29.380
didn't have five days.

29:30.780 --> 29:34.220
After three days, we were all ill because

29:34.220 --> 29:35.560
there wasn't any new air,

29:36.560 --> 29:38.440
but we didn't stop working.

29:39.380 --> 29:41.060
Captain Nemo worked with us.

29:41.590 --> 29:45.420
Then he said, into the submarine, all of

29:45.420 --> 29:45.580
you.

29:46.380 --> 29:48.440
There are only two metres of ice under

29:48.440 --> 29:49.020
us now.

29:50.120 --> 29:52.580
The Nautilus is going to do our work

29:52.580 --> 29:53.180
for us.

29:54.160 --> 29:56.440
The Nautilus was strong and heavy.

29:57.100 --> 30:00.200
It went down into our hole again and

30:00.200 --> 30:00.540
again.

30:01.560 --> 30:05.520
The ice started to move, and suddenly we

30:05.520 --> 30:06.780
were in open water.

30:08.420 --> 30:10.500
But there wasn't any air on the boat.

30:11.600 --> 30:14.180
And we were all very ill.

30:16.080 --> 30:17.680
The Nautilus moved under the ice.

30:18.520 --> 30:20.720
We waited and waited.

30:21.920 --> 30:25.380
I closed my eyes and started to sleep.

30:26.920 --> 30:27.960
Or was I dead?

30:30.400 --> 30:32.920
Then suddenly my eyes opened.

30:34.040 --> 30:34.500
What was that noise?

30:36.040 --> 30:38.340
The Nautilus is hitting ice again,

30:39.030 --> 30:41.680
but this ice's thing, Conce said.

30:42.580 --> 30:44.620
Perhaps we're going to be okay.

30:46.300 --> 30:48.720
The Nautilus tried again and again.

30:49.460 --> 30:51.660
First there were small holes in the ice.

30:52.480 --> 30:54.580
Then suddenly there was one big hole.

30:55.800 --> 30:57.200
The Nautilus went up into it.

30:58.000 --> 30:59.440
We weren't dead.

31:00.780 --> 31:02.160
We had air.

31:02.160 --> 31:02.320
Yeah.

31:06.840 --> 31:10.080
Chapter 7, goodbye to the Nautilus.

31:11.880 --> 31:15.120
After our visit to the Antarctic, we didn't

31:15.120 --> 31:16.780
see Captain Nemo very often.

31:18.000 --> 31:20.000
The Nautilus went up the coast of South

31:20.000 --> 31:21.060
and North America.

31:22.040 --> 31:25.800
We wanted to escape, but every night there

31:25.800 --> 31:26.360
was a problem.

31:27.240 --> 31:29.540
We weren't near the coast, or the sea

31:29.540 --> 31:30.340
was difficult.

31:31.600 --> 31:34.300
Then we went across the Atlantic to Europe

31:34.300 --> 31:36.800
and arrived in British waters.

31:38.300 --> 31:40.460
Suddenly there was a big noise.

31:41.340 --> 31:41.560
Boom!

31:42.500 --> 31:44.000
We looked across the sea.

31:44.980 --> 31:47.160
There was a big boat, three leagues away.

31:48.120 --> 31:50.740
It was that boat, Ned said.

31:51.580 --> 31:54.020
It wants to hit the Nautilus and kill

31:54.020 --> 31:54.500
us all.

31:55.420 --> 31:57.220
Which country is it from?

31:57.220 --> 31:57.560
I asked.

31:59.140 --> 32:00.400
I can't see!

32:01.140 --> 32:01.980
Ned answered.

32:03.060 --> 32:03.320
Boom!

32:04.160 --> 32:06.560
Water went up into the air only five

32:06.560 --> 32:07.780
meters from the Nautilus.

32:09.020 --> 32:10.440
Captain Nemo arrived.

32:11.440 --> 32:13.900
He was very angry, and he didn't look

32:13.900 --> 32:14.320
at us.

32:15.000 --> 32:16.800
He looked at the boat across the water

32:16.800 --> 32:17.460
and said,

32:18.180 --> 32:21.680
first you take my country and my family,

32:22.520 --> 32:24.780
and now you want to kill me too.

32:25.620 --> 32:27.500
But can you find me underwater?

32:28.760 --> 32:29.320
No.

32:30.240 --> 32:32.780
The Nautilus is going to hit your boat

32:32.780 --> 32:35.000
and kill you all.

32:35.960 --> 32:38.720
I wanted to stop the captain, but he

32:38.720 --> 32:39.800
didn't listen to me.

32:40.560 --> 32:43.520
The Nautilus moved away from the coast, and

32:43.520 --> 32:44.860
the boat came after us.

32:45.580 --> 32:46.980
Then we went underwater.

32:48.160 --> 32:50.100
For a short time it was quiet.

32:51.060 --> 32:53.420
Then we started to move very quickly.

32:53.420 --> 32:56.180
Suddenly the boat was in front of us.

32:56.880 --> 32:58.480
The Nautilus went into it.

32:59.460 --> 33:01.500
There was a big hole in the boat

33:01.500 --> 33:01.800
now.

33:03.040 --> 33:05.560
A lot of water went in, and the

33:05.560 --> 33:08.040
boat started to go down slowly under the

33:08.040 --> 33:08.300
sea.

33:09.580 --> 33:12.100
There were hundreds of men in the water.

33:13.580 --> 33:15.560
Captain Nemo watched them quietly.

33:17.080 --> 33:20.980
In a short time, they were all dead.

33:23.720 --> 33:25.500
Nemo went back to his bedroom.

33:27.400 --> 33:28.900
I looked at him from the door.

33:30.140 --> 33:32.740
He was on the floor, and in his

33:32.740 --> 33:35.220
hands there was a photograph of a beautiful

33:35.220 --> 33:36.080
young woman,

33:36.840 --> 33:40.560
and two small children, his dead family.

33:42.600 --> 33:45.480
After that unhappy day, we went up the

33:45.480 --> 33:46.900
coasts of Britain and Norway,

33:47.560 --> 33:49.320
and into the seas of the Arctic.

33:49.320 --> 33:53.700
For a week Ned Conce and I didn't

33:53.700 --> 33:55.340
see Captain Nemo and his men.

33:56.680 --> 33:58.420
Then one day Ned said,

33:59.200 --> 34:00.480
I can see the coast.

34:01.380 --> 34:05.140
It isn't near, but I can't stay on

34:05.140 --> 34:05.700
the Nautilus.

34:06.620 --> 34:09.600
I want to be home, or dead in

34:09.600 --> 34:09.960
the sea.

34:11.280 --> 34:13.600
I wanted to be away from the submarine,

34:13.960 --> 34:14.120
too.

34:15.160 --> 34:15.880
You're right, Ned.

34:16.460 --> 34:17.000
I answered.

34:17.920 --> 34:19.420
Let's escape this evening.

34:20.880 --> 34:22.940
I'm going to put food in the little

34:22.940 --> 34:23.240
boat.

34:24.020 --> 34:25.920
Be there at ten, he said.

34:26.820 --> 34:29.440
At ten o'clock, I went to the

34:29.440 --> 34:29.960
little boat.

34:30.820 --> 34:32.940
Ned and Conce were there before me.

34:33.820 --> 34:37.480
Okay, put the boat in the water, Ned

34:37.480 --> 34:37.800
said.

34:38.680 --> 34:41.460
But suddenly there were noises from Nemo's men.

34:42.200 --> 34:43.720
Did they know about our escape?

34:44.540 --> 34:45.740
The maelstrom!

34:46.320 --> 34:47.720
The maelstrom!

34:48.200 --> 34:49.440
The men said.

34:50.120 --> 34:52.360
This was a big problem.

34:53.620 --> 34:55.520
All seamen know about the maelstrom.

34:56.380 --> 34:58.380
Some of the seas of the Arctic move

34:58.380 --> 34:59.140
very quickly,

34:59.880 --> 35:01.720
and in one place two of those seas

35:01.720 --> 35:02.080
meet.

35:02.720 --> 35:05.720
There, a giant hole opens in the water.

35:06.580 --> 35:09.920
Boats and whales, ten leagues away, can't escape

35:09.920 --> 35:10.200
it.

35:11.020 --> 35:13.480
The maelstrom takes them all down to the

35:13.480 --> 35:14.020
sea floor.

35:15.160 --> 35:17.680
The maelstrom now wanted the nautilus.

35:18.500 --> 35:20.400
We looked at the big hole in the

35:20.400 --> 35:21.280
sea in front of us.

35:21.920 --> 35:25.440
The maelstrom's going to kill us, we said.

35:26.660 --> 35:29.840
It was a noise, and our little boat

35:29.840 --> 35:30.780
went into the sea.

35:31.740 --> 35:32.700
I went in, too.

35:33.640 --> 35:35.880
My head went under the water.

35:37.300 --> 35:38.700
Then my eyes closed.

35:40.600 --> 35:42.200
I opened my eyes.

35:43.400 --> 35:45.000
Ned and Conse were there.

35:46.500 --> 35:49.300
We were in the house of a Norwegian

35:49.300 --> 35:50.400
seamen.

35:51.860 --> 35:53.520
How did we get here?

35:54.460 --> 35:57.980
We don't remember, but in a short time

35:57.980 --> 35:58.880
we can go home.

36:00.060 --> 36:02.540
Every day we talk about the nautilus.

36:03.360 --> 36:06.720
We have a lot of questions, but perhaps

36:06.720 --> 36:08.520
we are never going to know the answers.

36:09.620 --> 36:12.020
Where did Captain Nemo come from?

36:13.220 --> 36:14.580
Who killed his family?

36:15.840 --> 36:18.740
Did he and his men escape from the

36:18.740 --> 36:19.220
maelstrom?

36:20.820 --> 36:22.720
And where is he now?

